@NODE about "About - What is it and why?"

In the last 2 years, in fact since I got my video cassette player, the amount of
cassettes  increased  drastically. More often I decided to replace one film with
another and had to rewrite the cassette lable. After several times of  replacing
films  this  didn't look good or was even readable (at least in my writing :). I
then found @{"PSVideo(TM)" link PSvideo} on AmiNet and after a short time I registered and had my
cassettes archived. Unfortunately PSVideo lacks the printing of cassette lables.
I decided to print the lables myself and to do it in LaTeX (since, as a  studend
of  physics, this is my favourite word processor!). That was done in one day (in
fact it was done in an hour, but I didn't like  the  result  so  I  reworked  it
several  times...:)  but  the work really began as I started to fill in the data
for every casette. I then contacted Holger Papajewski and asked him to implement
my  (or  any  other)  TeX-output  to  the  next version of his PSVideo! He first
decided to do so, but unfortionately dropped his work on PSVideo and Jörg Stumpf
(the other author) didn't want to implement TeX-output. The Idea of VideoLab was
born!

VideoLab is a frontend for LaTeX-Video-Cassette-Lables. You may  enter  all  the
data  needed  on  the cassette header and additional data on a lable (the bigger
one on the cassete side) and do several things more as adding backdrop  pictures
to  your lables using all the features @{"SpecialHost" link spech} has to offer.

You may choose from different template files or even create your own. If you use
PSVideo you may benefit from VideoLab's comfortable import function for  PSVideo
Databases.

Last but not least, VideoLab uses the most comfortable user interface, available
for the Amiga: @{"MUI 3.3" link mui}.

So give it a try and never have unreadable cassette lables and wasting your time
searching for a specific title!

Chris.




@ENDNODE

