@NODE requirements  "Requirements - What is needed to run VideoLab?"

VideoLab itself is not very demanding, I think it assumes about 200-300k of your
memory and at least kickstart version 2.04. VideoLab uses MUI 3.3 which consumes
much more memory and last but not least you need to have TeX installed  on  your
system.  TeX may be very memory consuming depending on which version you use. In
short:

   -  MUI 3.3        installed and running!

   -  (Pas)TeX       installed!

   -  200-300k       additional memory to that used by MUI!

   -  Kick 2.04+

If you want to use backdrop images with your  lables  you  need  Kickstart  3.0+
and the appropriate datatypes ( these are only used by SpecialHost/TeX ).

Should you discover any problems on any of those systems, please let me know!

@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE installing  "Installing VideoLab is quite easy!"

Right now there is no installation script,  since I don't know how to  make  one
and  don't  want  to  learn  it (now - of course later!). If there's anybody out
there who would like to do one, I would be pleased to include it in the package!

You must install VideoLab by hand, but it's rather simple. As  you  are  reading
this I expect you have already depacked the VideoLab archive - if not, do so!

Now just drag the VideoLab drawer to a place where you like it to be and add  an
assign to it to your s/user-startup

   assign VideoLab:  <place where you dragged the drawer>

That's it to run VideoLab with the included templates. You may of course replace
the  VideoLab Icon by another one (there should be some for NewIcons and MagicWB
included!). You may do this by just copying the icons - since  VideoLab  doesn't
use tooltypes, yet. Please make sure the stack is at least 8192 bytes.

There are two versions included, one for native 68k cpus and one  for  at  least
68020 cpus which should run on any processor higher than that, too. I named the
executables VideoLab.xxx where xxx is the processor. Copy the desired version to
"VideoLab" and it's done...

   Copy Videolab.xxx VideoLab

That's it! - Good TeXing...
