@NODE shortintro  "Quick Guide - For the impacient of you!"

I would really recommend reading the full introduction to get the  best  out  of
VideoLab and not only use the pre-configured things....

It follows a @{b}Step by Step@{ub} introduction...

   1) Install VideoLab on your system as defined @{"here" link installing}.

   2) Double click on the program icon to start it.

   3) Select the "Prefs"-Page by clicking on the page-ear in the upper right
      corner of the window.

   4) Fill in the fields. If you feel the pre-configured data fits your sys-
      tem please check this by clicking on the pop - symbol at the right end
      of the string gadgets.

      The fields have the following meanings:

      -  TeX-Application:        Fill in the complete path of you "virtex" -
                                 application.
      -  TeX-Format:             Enter the format which should be used by to
                                 TeX to compile your  lables.  These  format
                                 names  usually start with  a "&" character.
                                 Default  is  "&latex" which  is  a german -
                                 latex2e - format  file.  Refer to the TeX -
                                 documentation  if  you  don't  know what to
                                 enter in this field. You might try &glplain
                                 if you use PasTeX.

                                 Note: Which format to use depends on  which
                                 template you  are using.  All included ones
                                 have been tested  with LaTeX 2e,  but might
                                 also work with LaTeX 209.

      -  Preview Application:    As  you  may  have guessed,  enter the full
                                 path of your previewer-application here. If
                                 you use PasTeX, "TeX:bin/ShowDVI" is a good
                                 guess.
      -  DPI:                    Leave it unchanged, or read @{"this" link usage}.
      -  Use Pubscreen:          Check  this one  and enter  the name of the
                                 public  screen  to open  the previewer  on.
                                 This  is  an option  with ShowDVI,  I don't
                                 know if it works with others - it overrieds
                                 the ShowDVI's config data.

      -  Printer Application:    Enter  the full  path of  the PrintDVI-App.
                                 here.
      -  Pop GUI:                Uncheck!
      -  Use CheapDJ ...         Uncheck!

      -  Calculate Counter...:   You may  check this  one or  not. If  it's
                                 checked, VideoLab will calculate the start
                                 of  the next  film  title  on the cassette
                                 from the data inside the current "length"-
                                 and "counter start"-fields.

   5) So far! Now switch to the "Layout"-Page, by clicking on it's ear (top
      left edge of the window).

      VideoLab works through templates,  that is it just fills  in the data
      you gave it and combines 2 (one for the header and one for the lable)
      templates to a compilable tex-source file. You can select the  templ.
      for the header (long narrow cassette side) in the "Header-Template:"-
      field  and  do  the  same for  the lable.  Make  sure  you gave  full
      pathnames (no relative paths!).

      The syntax of the filenames is as follows:

      They start with either "head_" or "labl_" to indicate header-/lable-
      template files. Next comes a number  which indicates how many titles
      you may enter per cassette when using this template file. It doesn't
      makes sense to choose different  numbers in the  2 template  fields.
      The header template files  may have an additional  number at the end
      of the filename  before the  suffix.  This  one indicates wether the
      Tape ID  is composed  from 4 or 2 digits. 2 digits  looks better but
      might not suit your needs (IMHO).


   6) If you have already registered, you might switch  to the "PSVideo" -
      Page, enter a  complete pathname to  a PSVideo-dbase-file and select
      a cassette from the list of tapes which will then appear by double -
      clicking onto the entry or selecting  it via keyboard.  You can then
      generate  a tex - compilable  file hitting the "Generate" button  or
      even preview / print this lable  by  hitting the appropriate button.
      Note that you may not have enough memory to run TeX, the DVI-drivers
      and VideoLab at  the same time.  If this  is the case you may  leave
      VideoLab after generating a file and compile now...

      If not ...

      Choose the tape - type in the cycle gadget  on the left side of this
      page and enter the tape id into the right string gadget! Now  switch
      to the "Edit"-Page (selecting the ear, you know :)

   7) You may  discover disabled  fields.  This is not because of the demo
      version,  but because  not  all  template  files support every field
      VideoLab has to offer.

      The meaning of the fields should be clear! If not learn it by doing!

      That's it.


   For registered  users (they  hopefully  read the whole docs) there  are
   several menu items available. You may save/load a project which means a
   complete edites set of data which belongs  to the "Layout" and "Edit" -
   Pages. You may also save/load your preferences settings you made on the
   "Prefs"-page.

   And READ THE DOCS !!!

@ENDNODE

   ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

@NODE usage "Usage - A full introduction..."

Welcome to the full documentation of VideoLab. This documentation  may  be  used
via  on-line  help  out  of  VideoLab by pressing the "HELP"-Button at any time.
Short help is supported via bubble help - just move the mouse pointer above  the
object   you   want   help   for   and   wait   the  time  you  defined  in  the
MUI-Preferences-Editor.

The features of VideoLab are gathered on four so-called pages  corresponding  to
their functions. The four pages are


   @{"  " link GR_grp_layout}  The templates page

   @{"  " link GR_grp_edit}  The edit-page

   @{"  " link GR_psvideo}  The PSVideo import page

   @{"  " link GR_grp_prefs}  The preferences page


Before you refer to one of those pages it might be  helpful  to  understand  how
VideoLab works, that is its concept. VideoLab works through template files. This
means you create (or use predfined) files  which  are  complete  TeX  files  but
without  the  data  on the cassettes. At the appropriate places in the templates
you put keywords, which will be replaced by VideoLab with the data  you  entered
into  its fields. This way every user may define his/her personal outfit and use
it without changes to the program. If you want to learn how to  write  your  own
template  files,  take  a  look  at  the  @{"Own  Templates" link own_templates} section.

A few template files are included in the distribution of VideoLab. Any output of
VideoLab  is created from two template files, one for the header and one for the
lable, which may be put on the cassette side. The header normally  contains  the
titles,  the start positions and the lengths of the films as well as information
on the cassette (e.g. E-180,...) and a cassette id (e.g. 1,2,3...). The included
template  files  are  in  the  drawer  "templates"  and  their  names follow the
following syntax:

   - They always start with either "head_" or "labl_" defining header- or lable-
     template files.

   - Next comes a number which tells the maximum  number of titles this template
     is designed for.

   - Header templates may  offer an  additional number right  before the suffix,
     which tells you wether the type id is created from 2 or 4 digits.

Before  you  may  enter  any  cassette-specific  data  you  must  select  the  2
templatefiles,  because  VideoLab  will  only  enable fields which are supported
through the selected template files.

Before you start using VideoLab you should configure it to  match  your  system,
i.e.  mainly it has to fit you TeX installation. This is very important, because
VideoLab is designed as a frontend for TeX. If you want to use VideoLab only  to
generate  the  tex  files  you  compile  later  without the help of VideoLab, no
configuration for TeX is  needed.  However,  you  should  take  a  look  at  the
@{"Prefs-Page" link GR_grp_prefs} first.

Assuming you have made all necessary adjustments on the preferences page, I will
now explain how to generate a TeX-lable, using a included project as an example.

Please select the "Load" item of the "Project" menu or press Amiga+l.  You  will
now   be   prompted   by   a  standard  asl  file  requester.  Select  the  file
"Projects/Tape61.vlb".  This  will  load  all  the  data  for  the  "Edit"-  and
"Layout"-pages.  Please  refer  to  the Chapter about the @{"Layout-Page" link GR_grp_layout} to learn
about the adjustments to be made there. Switch  to  the  @{"Edit-Page" link GR_grp_edit}-Chapter  to
learn about how to enter the cassette data.

The data which is used to create a complete  output  file  is  spread  over  the
Layout- and Edit-Pages. The Layout-Page contains all data on the templates (i.e.
you define the layout of your output here), the optional backdrop images and the
cassette itself (that is tape-id and tape-type). The Edit-Page contains the data
on the films, that is their starting positions, length, record-modes and so  on.
After  you  have entered or loaded the data you may create a compilable TeX-file
by pressing the "Generate"-Button. You may also preview your  file  by  pressing
the  "Preview"-Button  or print it by pressing the "Print"-Button. Note that you
must have made all necessary adjustments on  the  Prefs-Page  to  have  VideoLab
using  TeX directly (Preview- and Print-Buttons). Both preview and printing work
as follows. At first VideoLab generates a TeX-file and asks you for a  name  and
path  where  to  save  it.  Then it calls your virtex application with the given
format file and  compiles  the  generated  file  this  way.  After  successfully
compiling  your  document, either dviprint or dvishow applications are launched.
Virtex is always called with the "-n" option  which  means  "nonstop-mode".  Any
errors  compiling  your file will be printed to the shell window (VideoLab opens
this), but TeX won't stop compiling - no input of yours is needed!

For further information,  please refer to the page nodes above.  Using the  menu
should be self-explaining...

@ENDNODE

@NODE GR_grp_layout  "The Layout-Page"

The layout page conatins all data which is cassette and layout specific! That is
you define here the templates to be used to create the tex-file and you may give
optionally filenames of backdrop images  to  be  used  (this  may  be  disabled,
depending on what template file you use!) and define the tape-type and -id.

The page is devided in  three  groups.  I  will  explain  the  field's  meanings
top/down...

                               @{b}Templates - Group@{ub}

Header Template   -  This field holds  a  complete path/filename of the template
                     file which should be used to define the header-layout (that
                     is the small side of the cassette). The botton at the right
                     side of this text field  pops up a standard  file requester
                     to ease selecting a template file. Templates are located in
                     the sub-drawer "templates/". You must give  full pathnames!
                     If  you want  to get a  header generated,  you must  give a
                     header template file...

Lable Template    -  This fields meaning is the same as the above field,  but is
                     used for the lable (side of the cassette).


                            @{b}Backdrop Images - Group@{ub}


Header Backdrop   -  This field holds the complete path/filename of the backdrop
                     image which should be used with the header - template file.
                     The usage of backdrop images is optional and depends on the
                     template file you use.  If the template  does not support a
                     backdrop image, this field will be disabled.

Lable Backdrop    -  The same as above, but for the lable template.


                               @{b}Tape Data - Group@{ub}

This Group doesn't have a border or a title, it's just the  two  elements  below
the Backdrop Images - Group.

The @{b}Cycle - Knob@{ub} on the left side of the window is determined to select the type
of  cassette  you  use  (i.e.  180, 200, 210, 240, 260 or 300 minute tapes). The
@{b}ID-field@{ub} on the right side is for the tape number. You may enter numbers  up  to
9999 here.

@ENDNODE

@NODE GR_grp_edit  "The Edit-Page"

This page should be self explaining... It is seperated into four sub-pages, each
for  one  film title. I think there's not much to say about the fileds meanings.
But as this is (or should be a documentation...:)

Film-Title        -  This  field  holds  the name  of the film.  You  are always
                     editing the  film which  is shown in the  active ear at the
                     top of the register. Please keep in  mind that depending on
                     the template  you chose  there may  not be enough  room for
                     long titles to fit. If a title becomes too long  it will be
                     shortened on  the lable  ending with three dots.  The  name
                     itself (inside VideoLab) will NOT be shortened.
Actor             -  You may  add the name of  one or more  main  actors of that
                     film. I must  repeat the words  I said to  the title field:
                     There might not be enough room on the lable ...!
Actrice           -  The same as above, but for our female companions...

Record Mode       -  This  cycle - button defines the  record mode  of the film,
                     either LP (long play) or SP (for standard play).
BBFC              -  This  cycle  selects between  the available  minimum ages a
                     "consumer" of this film should have.
Kind              -  You may give an explanation of the genre of this film. Keep
                     the length of your entry in  mind -  it may be shortened to
                     fit the lable.

Counter Start     -  This field  holds  the  start of  the actual  title in  the
                     format h:mm:ss. You may enter the start-position in minutes
                     and VideoLab will convert it to the above mentioned.
Length            -  This field holds the length of that title in minutes.

       @{b}Some words to film lenghts, starting positions and cassette types:@{ub}

You may have discovered the vertical  fuel  gauge  on  the  right  side  of  the
Edit-Group.  This  gauge  will  be  updated  corresponding to the tape type, the
lengths of the entered titles (respecting their record  modes!).  This  is  much
like  a  gag  of course but I thought it would be nice and wanted to make use of
one more MUI-Object (hehe :)!

I have added a nice (IMHO) feature to the counter-start field which  arose  from
the  fact  that  PSVideo  2.0  (which  I  used most of the time) doesn't support
counter positions in the format of  h:mm:ss  and  my  video  recorder  does  not
support the minutes only format. You might check the Calculate-Counter button on
the preferences page (bottom). If you do so, VideoLab will try to calculate  the
counter start of the nect title from the values in the Counter-Start and Lengths
fields. If you do not want this feature, unckeck the apropriate  button  in  the
prefs page.

@ENDNODE

@NODE GR_psvideo  "PSVideo-Import Page"

There's really not much to say about the PSVideo  import  function.  You  see  a
listview  and  a string-gadget with a pop-button on this page. The string gadget
should hold a complete path-/filename to the desired PSVideo-Database file.  You
may use the pop-button to get a standard asl requester to select the file. After
selecting a database, all cassettes will be displayed in the listview above. You
may  select the one to import into the Layout- and Edit-Pages by double-clicking
on it. You may of course select it by pressing the return-key on  your  keyboard
if you prefer keyboard handling.

To be able to import the actor-, actrice- and  bbfc-fields  correctly  you  must
define the title extensions in PSVideo as follows:

   Extension 2 has to be the actor-field,
   Extension 3 has to be the actrice-field,     and
   Extension 4 has to be the bbfc field.

Note that this function's use is restricted in the unregistered version.

@ENDNODE

@NODE GR_grp_prefs   "The Preferences Page"

This page contains all TeX-specific data, VideoLab uses to act as a frontend  to
TeX. That is ...

TeX-Application      -  A full path-/filename of your virtex-application, which
                        will be used to compile generated files.
                        The PopUp-Button at the right side  will ease selecting
                        the application.  Please keep in mind that  TeX usually
                        uses quite a bit of memory and that you  should not use
                        BigTeX  versions  because  of this.  VideoLab generates
                        files  which should  be small enough to  be compiled by
                        the normal versions.
TeX-Format           -  This field defines the format file to be used by VirTeX
                        including  the "&" - character.  The default is &latex,
                        which is the german latex2e format file (on my system)!

Preview Application  -  Give the full pathname of your ShowDVI - Application to
                        be used to preview compiled dvi-files.

The following two  fields may not  be supported by ShowDVI drivers,  other than
ShowDVI from the PasTeX package...

DPI                  -  You may give a number here which represents the dpi-re-
                        solution which  should be  used by  the previer to show
                        the generated/compiled file.
Use-Pubscreen        -  When Checked, the ShowDVI-Application  will be asked to
                        open its window on the given public screen ( default is
                        the workbench screen!)

Printer-Application  -  This field holds  the complete pathname of  the printer-
                        driver used to print the generated/compiled files.

The following two  fields may not  be supported by DVIprint drivers,  other than
DVIprint from the PasTeX package...

Pop up GUI           -  When checked, DVIprint  application will pop up a user -
                        interface for enhanced control.
Use CheapDJ...       -  This turns on a special mode of  the HP-Deskjet printer-
                        series which should use less ink (but doesn' t look that
                        good!).


Calculate Counter... -  When checked,  Counter start  positions of  film  titles
                        will be  calculated from  previous starting position and
                        length. For more explanation, refer to the @{"Edit-Page" link GR_grp_edit}.


@ENDNODE

@NODE own_templates  "Creating your own template files"

First of all: If you create new template files, I would like to ask you to  send
them to me (please include a demo-dvi file) so I can include them in the package
and other users may benefit from your work. Thanks in advance!

The template files define the layout of your output file. I  have  splitted  the
templates  into  header  and  label files. In the TeX/ directory you will find a
file "Imbed.tex" which will be used by VideoLab to merge the  header  and  label
templates  together  to  form  a  complete  tex  file.  Imbed.tex  contains  the
TeX-preamble (you know, \documentstyle{} or ...class under LaTeX 2e...) and  the
\begin{}-,  \end{}-document commands. The best explanation of the Imbed.tex file
will be to look at it...

To create your own template file you should be familiar with LaTeX  and/or  TeX.
You  must  define  your template to fit a cassette header/lable. I have used the
xfig program, which has been ported to the amiga by Terje  Pederson,  to  design
the  output  file. Then I converted the fig-file to a latex-file using eepic and
epic picture enhancements and replaced the titles, lengths and so  on  with  the
apropriate  keyword  strings.  I  have  included  the fig-files in the templates
drawer - if you want to create a new template based on the  existing  ones.  You
find a listing of those keywords @{"here" link keywords}.

Please name your own templates, obeying the syntax I have defined and  explained
above since it makes it a lot easier to select the template files from VideoLab.

I think that's it!
Not? - Mail me, phone me, meet me....                    (last one preferred! :)

@ENDNODE

