@NODE keywords "The template file - keywords strings"

Here is a complete list of keywords understood by VideoLab and to be used in the
template  files.  Please  take a look at the included templates, before creating
templates yourself - it might prevent some faults.

                                @{b}LENGTH KEYWORDS@{ub}


First you should provide the length keywords which give the maximum  lengths  of
the  title-,  length-,  kind/genre-,  actor-  and actrice-fields. Those keywords
should start with a "%" character at the first position of a  line,  since  they
won't be replaced or deleted - they just provide some additional information for
VideoLab. You should take precautions to make  shure  they  won't  corrupt  your
output-files.

   %HTLEN=<value>       ...   <value>  gives  the maximum characters  a title is
                              allowed to have in the header-template.

   %LTLEN=<value>       ...   this is the same for  the lable.  This value might
                              differ the above one.

   %KIND=<value>        ...   maximum number  of characters for  the genre/kind-
                              string. (Only lable templates!)

   %HLEN=<value>        ...   maximum number of characters for the actors field
                              (Only lable template!)

   %SLEN=<value>        ...   the same but for the actrice field.

Please note that at the current version of VideoLab the  usage  of  keywords  is
bound to the type of template file (header or lable)!

                                @{b}HEADER KEYWORDS@{ub}

The following keywords may be used inside header-template-files...

   $TIME_1                     |
   $TIME_2                     |             -> `h:mm:ss'
   $TIME_3                     |
   $TIME_4                     | -> these keywords will be replaced by the
                                    counter-start positions of the apropriate
                                    titles in the format h:mm:ss.

   $HTITLE_1                   |
   $HTITLE_2                   |
   $HTITLE_3                   |
   $HTITLE_4                   | -> these will be replaced by the film-titles,
                                    regarding the HTLEN - keyword.

   $LEN_1                      |
   $LEN_2                      |             -> `<value> min'
   $LEN_3                      |
   $LEN_4                      | -> will be replaced with the length of the
                                    apropriate film titles (in minutes).


   The tape id is build from up to 4 picture files (for the rotated numbers).
   You may give only the keywords for no 2 and 3 without 1 and 4 - this will
   make VideoLab build the tape id from 2 digits and might look a bit better.

   $NR_1                         -> `<digit-value>.iff'  the top/first digit
   $NR_2                         ->          -"-         the one below that one.
   $NR_3                         ->          -"-         the one below that one.
   $NR_4                         ->          -"-         the one below that one.

   $CASSLEN                      -> `E-<value>.iff'      will give the filename
                                                         without path of the
                                                         cassette type.

                                 @{b}LABEL KEYWORDS@{ub}

The following keywords might be used inside lable template files...


   $HDAR_IN_1                  |
   $HDAR_IN_2                  |          %SLEN field will be obeyed !!!
   $HDAR_IN_3                  |
   $HDAR_IN_4                  | ->    <string> name of actrice in apropriate films

   $HDARST_1                   |
   $HDARST_2                   |          %HLEN field will be obeyed !!!
   $HDARST_3                   |
   $HDARST_4                   | ->    <string> name of actor ...

   $FSK_1                      |
   $FSK_2                      |
   $FSK_3                      |
   $FSK_4                      | ->    <value>  (the one selected in the bbfc field)

   $LTITLE_1                   |
   $LTITLE_2                   |          %LTLEN field will be obeyed !!!
   $LTITLE_3                   |
   $LTITLE_4                   | ->    <string> name of the film titles ...
                                       

   $TIME_1                     |
   $TIME_2                     |
   $TIME_3                     |
   $TIME_4                     | ->    same as in the header template file.

   $LEN_1                      |
   $LEN_2                      |
   $LEN_3                      |
   $LEN_4                      | ->    same as in the header template file.

   $REC_1                      |
   $REC_2                      |
   $REC_3                      |
   $REC_4                      | ->    'SP' or 'LP' depending on record mode.

   $RUBR_1                     |
   $RUBR_2                     |
   $RUBR_3                     |
   $RUBR_4                     | ->    <string> kind/genre of that film.


Note that you can not assume that titles and other length restricted fields are
completely displayed on the lable.


@ENDNODE

@NODE psusers "You are a registered PSVideo user!"

Jörg  and  Holger  suggested  to  modify  the  existing  restrictions   in   the
unregistered  versions  so  that  the  unregistered  version  is  of  any use to
psvideo-users. I did change them according to their suggestions...

   PSVideo Import is enabled, but reduced in its function such as only the first
   title of the selected cassette is imported.  I think this way you get  a good
   impression of how the import function would work after registering...

I hope that this causes not too much people not to pay for VideoLab, since  this
project is a test of shareware to me (and I want to get a bit money for the work
I put into VideoLab :)



@ENDNODE
